<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="562" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,797,1758]" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,431,869,894]" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Diagnosis of male.</emphasis>
Dorsal surface of head, pronotum, and tergite IV coarsely punctate; antennomeres subquadrate; elytra with deep sutural and discal striae; first protarsomere with long protuberance at apex; tergites VI–VII modified, VI concave, with two long lateral projections, VII strongly concave at base; aedeagus with relatively short and broad ventral and dorsal lobes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="562" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,797,1758]" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1013,1038]" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Description.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[426,490,1013,1038]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1635,1657]" captionTargetBox="[156,1432,311,1602]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,303,1611]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male habitus of Batriscenellus besucheti (with right protarsi enlarged) (A), and B. carltoni (B). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887866/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A). Body reddish-brown, length 
<quantity box="[862,966,1014,1038]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.99" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="1.99">1.99 mm</quantity>
. Head subrectangular, slightly wider than long, HL 
<quantity box="[266,371,1050,1074]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="0.41">0.41 mm</quantity>
, HW 
<quantity box="[443,548,1050,1074]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="0.44">0.44 mm</quantity>
, dorsal surface coarsely punctate, with large and round punctures (
<figureCitation box="[1329,1400,1049,1074]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1500,1522]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1472]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,447,1475]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of male Batriscenellus (A, C, E – F. B. besucheti; B, D, G – H. B. carltoni). A – B. Head dorsum and pronotum. C – D. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view. E – H. Aedeagus, in lateral (E, G) and ventral (F, H) views. Scale bars: 0.2 mm in A – D; 0.1 mm in E – H." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887868/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
A); vertex with median ridge anteriorly connected with U-shaped sulcus that connects foveae; antennomeres subquadrate, clubs loosely formed by apical three antennomeres; each eye composed of about 20 facets. Pronotum about as long as wide, PL 
<quantity box="[457,561,1157,1182]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="0.45">0.45 mm</quantity>
, PW 
<quantity box="[625,729,1157,1182]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.6" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="0.46">0.46 mm</quantity>
, coarsely punctate (
<figureCitation box="[957,1027,1157,1182]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1500,1522]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1472]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,447,1475]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of male Batriscenellus (A, C, E – F. B. besucheti; B, D, G – H. B. carltoni). A – B. Head dorsum and pronotum. C – D. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view. E – H. Aedeagus, in lateral (E, G) and ventral (F, H) views. Scale bars: 0.2 mm in A – D; 0.1 mm in E – H." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887868/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
A). Elytra wider than long, EL 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="0.58">0.58 mm</quantity>
, EW 
<quantity box="[259,362,1194,1218]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.199999999999999" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="0.72">0.72 mm</quantity>
, narrowed at base, discal striae extending to near elytral apex, curved laterally at apices; sutural striae complete. First protarsomeres (
<figureCitation box="[567,630,1229,1254]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1635,1657]" captionTargetBox="[156,1432,311,1602]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,303,1611]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Male habitus of Batriscenellus besucheti (with right protarsi enlarged) (A), and B. carltoni (B). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887866/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
A) with long setose projection at apices. Abdomen wider than long, AL 
<quantity box="[151,253,1265,1290]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="0.55">0.55 mm</quantity>
, AW 
<quantity box="[317,420,1266,1290]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.70 mm</quantity>
, coarsely punctate and with long setae; tergite VI (
<figureCitation box="[993,1060,1265,1290]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1500,1522]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1472]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,447,1475]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of male Batriscenellus (A, C, E – F. B. besucheti; B, D, G – H. B. carltoni). A – B. Head dorsum and pronotum. C – D. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view. E – H. Aedeagus, in lateral (E, G) and ventral (F, H) views. Scale bars: 0.2 mm in A – D; 0.1 mm in E – H." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887868/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
C) concave, with two long lateral projections, tergite VII (
<figureCitation box="[421,487,1301,1326]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1500,1522]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1472]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,447,1475]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of male Batriscenellus (A, C, E – F. B. besucheti; B, D, G – H. B. carltoni). A – B. Head dorsum and pronotum. C – D. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view. E – H. Aedeagus, in lateral (E, G) and ventral (F, H) views. Scale bars: 0.2 mm in A – D; 0.1 mm in E – H." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887868/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
C) strongly concave at base. Aedeagus strongly asymmetric, length 
<quantity box="[1245,1347,1302,1326]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.9" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" unit="mm" value="0.29">0.29 mm</quantity>
, ventral lobe elongate, broad at base and narrowing toward apex, curved leftwards in ventral view; dorsal lobe longer than ventral lobe, broad and curved ventrally, acute at apex (
<figureCitation box="[772,839,1373,1398]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1500,1522]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,447,1472]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,447,1475]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Diagnostic features of male Batriscenellus (A, C, E – F. B. besucheti; B, D, G – H. B. carltoni). A – B. Head dorsum and pronotum. C – D. Abdominal tergites IV – VII, in dorsal view. E – H. Aedeagus, in lateral (E, G) and ventral (F, H) views. Scale bars: 0.2 mm in A – D; 0.1 mm in E – H." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/887868/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
E–F).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,797,1758]" box="[151,365,1409,1434]" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Female. Unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,797,1758]" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,443,1445,1470]" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Comparative Notes.</emphasis>
The new species is morphologically similar to the other three new Indian species described below. These species share coarsely punctate heads, pronota, and tergites IV, a similar position of the male abdominal modifications, and form a distinct 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2017" box="[750,891,1517,1541]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Batriscenellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="besucheti">
<emphasis box="[750,767,1518,1541]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[785,891,1517,1541]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">besucheti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group (here termed) within the genus. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2017" box="[151,423,1553,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Batriscenellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="besucheti">
<emphasis box="[151,423,1553,1577]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">Batriscenellus besucheti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be readily separated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2017" box="[764,884,1553,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Batriscenellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carltoni">
<emphasis box="[764,781,1554,1577]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[795,884,1553,1577]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">carltoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2017" box="[897,1052,1553,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Batriscenellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuccodoroi">
<emphasis box="[897,914,1554,1577]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[927,1052,1553,1577]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">cuccodoroi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yin" authorityYear="2017" box="[1113,1207,1553,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Batriscenellus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loebli">
<emphasis box="[1113,1130,1554,1577]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">B</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1143,1207,1553,1577]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="562">loebli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the protarsomere I having a long setose projection at the apex, a unique character lacking in all other congeners. Otherwise, the presence of two projections at the posterior margin of tergite VI, the basally strongly concave tergite VII, and form of the aedeagus also help to clearly separated the new species from similar relatives.
</paragraph>
